Its very truncate base, thick midrib, and thiu, closely spaced, widely diver- gent secondaries are easily recognizable and diagnostic.

This type of leaf is by far the most abundant at Locality P. 374. Over 25 well-preserved specimens were collected for study. The majority of these cannot be distinguished in any essential detail from the type specimens from Black Buttes, Wyoming. These were originally described as Aleurites cocenim by Lesquereux, who subsequently changed the name to Grewz'opsis saportana. In a later report Knowlton changed the name again to Grew‘iopsis cocenim, a procedure which hardly seems justified, as has been pointed out by Brown. Knowlton also included Ward’s specimens of Grewz'ops'z's ficisolz'a in this species, a reference clearly substantiated by the numerous Medicine Bow specimens. In view of the large number of variants now available it seems appro- priate to re-describe the species.
